Title: Implementing the Time-varying Minimum Variance Portfolio¶

Eshan Kaul

Background¶

In recent years, the field of investment management has been actively seeking ways to improve the accuracy and efficiency of portfolio optimization techniques. One such technique is the minimum variance portfolio (MVP), which aims to construct a portfolio with the lowest possible variance given a set of constraints.

However, the traditional MVP approach assumes a constant covariance matrix, which can be problematic in a dynamic setting where the correlations between assets are likely to change over time. This can lead to suboptimal investment decisions and potentially significant losses for investors.

To address this issue, researchers have proposed various extensions of the MVP approach, including the time-varying minimum variance portfolio (TV-MVP). The TV-MVP allows for time-varying factor loadings and considers the dynamics of the asset returns' covariance structure, making it a potentially valuable tool for investment managers operating in a dynamic environment.

Despite the potential benefits of TV-MVP, there is still a need for further research in this area. Specifically, there is a need for robust statistical methods to estimate the time-varying covariance matrix and to construct the optimal portfolio with a consistent risk-return trade-off.

The paper "Time-varying Minimum Variance Portfolio" by Qingliang Fan et al. proposes a new method for constructing a time-varying minimum variance portfolio (TV-MVP) and provides empirical evidence of its effectiveness. As a reader interested in replicating the study's results, the focus will be on reproducing the methodology described in the paper and verifying the findings. The paper's contributions to the literature, including the use of time-varying factor loadings and a shrinkage estimation method to regularize the residual covariances, will be explored in detail, with an emphasis on understanding the theoretical properties of the proposed TV-MVP and its consistency with respect to the Sharpe ratio and risk consistency. The simulations and empirical analysis presented in the paper will be replicated, with a particular focus on evaluating the proposed TV-MVP's performance in terms of estimation accuracy and out-of-sample Sharpe ratio, and comparing it to other popular contemporary methods. By replicating the study's results, this analysis aims to contribute to the existing literature on TV-MVP and portfolio optimization, as well as provide a better understanding of the methodology and findings presented in the original paper.

Minimum Variance Portfolio¶

$$ \begin{aligned} & \min W^{\top} \Sigma_r W \\ & \text { s.t. } W^{\top} 1_p=1 . \end{aligned} $$

where $\Sigma_r$ is the constant $p$-dimensional population covariance matrix of asset returns; $W$ is a $p \times 1$ vector of asset weights in the portfolio, and $1_p$ is a $p \times 1$ vector of 1 's. The analytical solution for MVP weight is: $$ W^*=\frac{\Sigma_r^{-1} 1_p}{1_p^{\top} \Sigma_r^{-1} 1_p} $$ The variance of MVP and the corresponding Sharpe ratio (SR) are: $$ \begin{gathered} R_{\min }=W^{* \top} \Sigma_r W^*=\frac{1}{1_p^{\top} \Sigma_r^{-1} 1_p} \\ \mathrm{SR}=\frac{W^{* \top} \mu}{\sqrt{W^{* \top} \Sigma_r W^*}}=\frac{1_p^{\top} \Sigma_r^{-1} \mu}{\sqrt{1_p^{\top} \Sigma_r^{-1} 1_p}} . \end{gathered} $$

Time-varying Minimum Variance Portfolio¶

The expected return of financial assets is modeled by several finite common factors Rothschild (1983). Excess assets return can be modeled as:

$$r_{it} = b^T_{it}F_{t}+e_{it}, \quad i=1,2,\ldots,p; \quad t=1,2,\ldots,T,$$

where $r_{it}$ is the return of asset $i$ at time, $t$, $F_{t}$ is the $m$-dimensional vector of common factors at time $t$ and $b_{it}$is the $m \times 1$ factor loading that captures the relationships between the common factors and asset $i$ at time $t$. $e_{it}$ is the idiosyncratic error. For this project assume unobserved factors however, in practice factors can be either observed or unobserved. The factors and loadings are obtained using principal component analysis.

Decomposing the covariance matrix of the assets (necessary for synthesizing the portfolio weights):

$$\Sigma_{r,t}=B_{t}\Sigma_{F}B^T_{t} + \Sigma_{e}, \quad t = 1, 2,\ldots, T,$$

where $\Sigma_{F}$ is the covariance matrix of the common factors (assumed to be time-invariant and positive definite), and $\Sigma_{e}$ is the covariance matrix of the idiosyncratic errors.

The steps for model estimation are as follows:

  1. Simultaneously estimate time-varying factor loading $B_{t}$ and common factors $F_{t}$
  2. Get the idiosyncratic residual, and further derive sparse covariance matrix estimator of residuals $\Sigma_{e}$
  3. estimate the covariance matrix of return by $B_{t}\Sigma_{F}B^T_{t} + \Sigma_{e}$

The final TV-MVP strategy is to allocate the assets in the protfolio using the following weights:

$$\widehat{W_{t}} = \frac{\hat{\Sigma}^{-1}_{r,t}1_{p}}{1^{T}_{p}\hat{\Sigma}^{-1}_{r,t}1_{p}}$$

Data Generating Process¶

The simulation data generating process with $m=2$ common factors are generated as:

\begin{aligned} & f_{1, t}=\mu_{f 1}+0.6 f_{1, t-1}+u_{1, t}, u_{1, t} \stackrel{i i d}{\sim} N\left(0,1-0.6^2\right) \\ & f_{2, t}=\mu_{f 2}+0.3 f_{2, t-1}+u_{2, t}, u_{2, t} \stackrel{i i d}{\sim} N\left(0,1-0.3^2\right) \end{aligned}

where $u_{i, t}$ and $\mu_{f i}$ for $\mathrm{i}=1,2$ are disturbance and intercept terms, respectively, and $f_{1,0}=f_{2,0}=0$.

Setting (1): Step function type factor loadings. The factor loadings $b_{i t}=\left(b_{i t}^{(1)}, b_{i t}^{(2)}\right)^T$ are set to be the step functions as follows:

$$ b_{i t}^{(1)}=\left\{\begin{array}{rll} 2\left|z_i^{(1)}\right| & \text { for } & 1 \leq t \leq D \\ 2\left|z_i^{(1)}\right|+z_i^{(2)} & \text { for } & D+1 \leq t \leq 2 D \\ 2\left|z_i^{(1)}\right|+z_i^{(2)}+z_i^{(3)} & \text { for } & 2 D+1 \leq t \leq 3 D \\ \vdots & & \\ 2\left|z_i^{(1)}\right|+\sum_{j=2}^k z_i^{(j)} & \text { for } & (k-1) D+1 \leq t \leq k D \\ & & \end{array}\right. $$

where $z_i^{(j)}$ for $j=1,2, \ldots, K$ are standard normal random variables, and $D$ is the length of each step $(K=T / D$ steps total $) . b_{i t}^{(2)}$ has the similar form as $b_{i t}^{(1)}$ by replacing $z_i^{(j)}$ by $\left|v_i^{(j)}\right|$ and $v_i^{(j)} \sim N(0,1)$ for $j=1,2, \ldots, K$. For this DGP, the values of parameter $D$ is given by 25,50 and 100 for $p=50,100,200$, respectively.

Setting (2): Time-varying smooth function type factor loadings. For this setting,

$$ b_{i t}^{(1)}=\left(3+z_i^{(1)}\right) t / T+z_i^{(2)} \sin (4 \pi t / T)+z_i^{(3)} $$

where $z^{(j)}, j=1,2,3$ are standard normal random variables. And,

$$ b_{i t}^{(2)}=\left(3+z_i^{(1)}\right) t / T+z_i^{(2)} \sin (4 \pi t / T)+\left(z_i^{(4)} t / T\right)^2+z_i^{(3)} $$

where the extra square term is added to distinguish it with $b_{i t}^{(1)}$ and also amplify the variations in factor loadings.

import numpy as np

"""
Discription: 
    Data Generating Process

Inputs: 
    (1) p is the dimension of the portfolio
    (2) T is sample size
    (3) rho controls the departure from constant factor loading
    
Outputs:
    (1) Y is generated return data
    (2) r_cov is population return covariance matrix
    (3) s_cov is Σe
"""
def data_generate(p, T, rho):
    np.random.seed(2)
    subt = np.arange(1, T+1) / T
    
    # generate the smooth time varying factor loading
    loading1 = np.zeros((p, T))
    loading2 = np.zeros((p, T))
    for subi in range(p):
        z = rho * ((3 + np.random.randn()) * subt + np.random.randn() * np.sin(4 * np.pi * subt)) + np.random.randn()
        z2 = rho * ((3 + np.random.randn()) * subt + np.random.randn() * np.sin(4 * np.pi * subt) + (np.random.randn() * subt) ** 2) + np.random.randn()
        loading1[subi, :] = z
        loading2[subi, :] = z2

    # cross-sectional dependence in residuals
    s_cov = np.zeros((p, p))
    for i in range(p):
        for j in range(i+1, p):
            s_cov[i, j] = (0.5) ** abs(j - i)
            s_cov[j, i] = s_cov[i, j]
    np.fill_diagonal(s_cov, 1)
    r_cov = np.dot(np.concatenate((loading1[:, -1:], loading2[:, -1:]), axis=1), np.concatenate((loading1[:, -1:], loading2[:, -1:]), axis=1).T) + s_cov

    F1_set = np.zeros(T+200)
    F2_set = np.zeros(T+200)
    F1_t0 = np.random.randn()
    F2_t0 = np.random.randn()
    for j in range(T+200):
        F1_t = 0.6 * F1_t0 + np.random.normal(0, 0.8)
        F1_set[j] = F1_t
        F1_t0 = F1_t
        F2_t = 0.3 * F2_t0 + np.random.normal(0, 0.91)
        F2_set[j] = F2_t
        F2_t0 = F2_t
    F = np.concatenate((F1_set[200:200+T].reshape(-1, 1), F2_set[200:200+T].reshape(-1, 1)), axis=1)

    x_k = np.random.multivariate_normal(np.zeros(p), s_cov, T).T

    fa_part = np.zeros((p, T))
    for qq in range(T):
        B1_temp = np.concatenate((loading1[:, qq].reshape(-1, 1), loading2[:, qq].reshape(-1, 1)), axis=1)
        fa_part[:, qq] = np.dot(B1_temp, F[qq, :])
    Y = fa_part + x_k
    return Y, r_cov, s_cov

Factor-augmented Penalized Likelihood Estimation¶

The penalized quasi-liklihood estimation approach is used to estimate factor loading $B_{t}$, common factor $F_{t}$, and residuals covariance matrix $\Sigma_{e}$.

$$ \left(\widehat{B}_t, \widehat{F}_t, \widehat{\Sigma}_e\right)=\arg \min _{\left(B_t, F_t, \Sigma_e\right)}\left\{\log \operatorname{det}\left(\Sigma_e\right)+\operatorname{tr}\left(\Sigma_e^{-1} \widetilde{S}_e\right)+\left\|\Lambda * \Sigma_e\right\|_1\right\} $$

where $\widetilde{S}_e=\frac{1}{T} \sum_{t=1}^T e_t e_t^{\top}$ with $e_t=r_t-B_t F_t$. $\Lambda$ is the non-negative arbitrary $p \times p$ tuning matrix, $*$ denotes the element-wise multiplication operator. Only the off-diagonal elements of the covariance matrix are penalized and the diagonal values of $\Lambda$ are set to zeros.

The challenge of solving the above equation comes from unobserved $e_t$ due to unknown parameters $B_t$ and oftentimes, unobservable $F_t$. To obtain the estimation the following two-step estimation procedure is taken:

  1. Estimate the factor model (both factor loadings and common factors)
  2. Solve the optimization problem using the estimated error components

Estimation of time-varying factor model¶

A single-regime factor loading assumption over a long time period in the factor model is often too restrictive for several reasons:

  1. Technological progress
  2. Sentimental changes
  3. Market turbulence
  4. Economic shocks
  5. Large number of assets in consideration in the portfolio

Instead choose to relax this assumption by considering the factor loadings to be time-variant.

Let $R$ denote the $p \times T$ data matrix of assets' returns, and $r_{i t}$ is the $(i, t)$-th element of matrix $R$.

Useing the local weighted least squares method Su and Wang (2017) to simultaneously estimate time-varying factor loading and common factors. Suppose the factor loading at time $x$ around $t, b_{i t} \approx b_{i x}$. Then solve the following optimization problem:

$$ \min _{\left\{b_{i x}\right\}_{i=1}^p,\left\{F_t\right\}_{t=1}^T}(p T)^{-1} \sum_{i=1}^p \sum_{t=1}^T\left(r_{i t}-b_{i x}^{\top} F_t\right)^2 K_h\left(\frac{t-x}{T}\right), $$

where $K_h(\cdot)=h^{-1} K(\cdot / h)$, $K(\cdot)$ is a kernel function and $h$ is a bandwidth parameter. This local weighted least squares problem can be rewritten as the following:

$$ \min _{\left(F^{(x)}, B_x\right)} \operatorname{tr}\left(\left(R^{(x)}-F^{(x)} B_x^{\top}\right)\left(R^{(x)}-F^{(x)} B_x^{\top}\right)^{\top}\right), $$

where $R^{(x)}=\left(R_1^{(x)}, \ldots, R_p^{(x)}\right), R_i^{(x)}=\left(k_{h, 1 x}^{1 / 2} r_{i 1}, \ldots, k_{h, T x}^{1 / 2} r_{i T}\right)^{\top}$ and $k_{h, t x}=h^{-1} K((t-x) / T h)$, for $i=1,2, \ldots, p . F^{(x)}$ is a $T \times m$ factor matrix, $m$ is the number of factors, and $B_x$ is the factor loading for time $x$. The identification conditions are:

$F^{(x)^{\top}} F^{(x)} / T=I_m, B_x^{\top} B_x$ is a diagonal matrix.

$\widehat{F}^{(x)}$ is $\sqrt{T}$ times $m$ largest eigenvectors of matrix $R^{(x)} R^{(x)^{\top}}$, and $\widehat{B}_x^{\top}=\widehat{F}^{(x)^{\top}} R^{(x)} / T$. Since the estimator $\widehat{F}^{(x)}$ is consistent with a rotated factor, the estimator for factor is given by $\widehat{F}_t=\left(\sum_{i=1}^p \widehat{b}_{i t} \widehat{b}_{i t}^{\top}\right)^{-1}\left(\sum_{i=1}^p \widehat{b}_{i t} r_{i t}\right)$ for $t=1,2, \ldots, T$ where $\widehat{B}_x=$ $\left(\widehat{b}_{1 x}, \ldots, \widehat{b}_{p x}\right)^{\top}$. Denote $\widehat{F}$ as the $m \times T$ matrix of estimated factors. The sample covariance matrix is $\widehat{\Sigma}_F=\frac{1}{T} \widehat{F} \widehat{F}^{\top}$. The number of factors can be determined using an information criterion.

To solve the boundary bias problem the following boundary kernel is used: $$ k_{h, t \tau}^*=h^{-1} K_\tau^*\left(\frac{t-\tau}{T h}\right)= \begin{cases}h^{-1} K\left(\frac{t-\tau}{T h}\right) / \int_{-(\tau / T h)}^{\infty} K(u) d u, & \text { if } \tau \in[0,\lfloor T h\rfloor) \\ h^{-1} K\left(\frac{t-\tau}{T h}\right), & \text { if } \tau \in[\lfloor T h\rfloor, T-\lfloor T h\rfloor] \\ h^{-1} K\left(\frac{t-\tau}{T h}\right) / \int_{-\infty}^{(1-\tau / T) / h} K(u) d u, & \text { if } \tau \in(T-\lfloor T h\rfloor, T]\end{cases} $$ take Epanechnikov kernel $K(u)=\frac{3}{4}\left(1-u^2\right) \mathbb{1}(|u| \leq 1)$.

Silverman's rule of thumb is used for the value of the bandwidth $h = \left(\frac{2.35}{\sqrt{12}}\right)T^{-0.2}p^{-0.1}$

from scipy.integrate import quad

"""
Description: 
    Epanechnikov kernel

Inputs: 
    (1) T is sample size.
    (2) t is the time point around target.
    (3) x is the target point.
    (4) h is bandwidt
    
Outputs:
    (1): result gives the value of K^{∗}_{x}(\frac{(t−x)}{Th})
"""
def Kernel(T, t, x, h):
    d1 = (t - x) / (T * h)
    f = lambda d: 0.75 * (1 - d**2) * (np.abs(d) <= 1)
    if x < T * h:
        int1, _ = quad(f, -x / (T * h), 1)
        result = f(d1) / int1
    elif x > (T - T * h):
        int1, _ = quad(f, -1, (1 - x / T) / h)
        result = f(d1) / int1
    else:
        result = f(d1)
    return result

Determining the number of factors (BIC)¶

$$ \widehat{m}=\arg \min _m I C(m) $$

where $I C(m)=\log V\left(m,\left\{\check{B}_x(m)\right\}\right)+\frac{p+T h}{p T h} \log \left(\frac{p T h}{p+T h}\right) m$, and $$ V\left(m,\left\{\check{B}_x(m)\right\}\right)=\min _{\check{F}=\left(\check{F}_1, \ldots, \check{F}_T\right)^{\top}} \frac{1}{p T} \sum_{i=1}^p \sum_{x=1}^T\left[r_{i x}-\check{b}_{i x}(m)^{\top} \check{F}_x\right]^2 $$ where $\check{B}_x(m)=(p T)^{-1} R^{(x)^{\top}} R^{(x)} \widehat{B}_x(m)$ for $x=1,2, \ldots, T$, and $\widehat{B}_x(m)=\left(\widehat{b}_{1 x}(m), \ldots, \widehat{b}_{p x}(m)\right)^{\top}$

"""
Description: 
    Estimate the number of factors using BIC-type information criterion

Inputs: 
    (1) T is sample size.
    (2) t is the time point around target.
    (3) x is the target point.
    (4) h is bandwidt
    
Outputs:
    (1): result gives the value of K^{∗}_{x}(\frac{(t−x)}{Th})
"""
def factor_number_selection(R, max_number):
    IC_R_set = []
    N, T = R.shape
    h = (2.35 / np.sqrt(12)) * (T ** -0.2) * (N ** -0.1)
    Kernel_set = np.zeros((T, T))
    for r in range(T):
        for t in range(T):
            k = (h ** -1) * Kernel(T, t, r, h)
            Kernel_set[t, r] = k ** 0.5

    for f_count in range(1, max_number+1):
        Factor_loadings, Factor, X_r_cell, _, h = Timevarying_factor_model(R, f_count, Kernel_set, h)
        Lambda_wan_set = []
        for r in range(T):
            X_r_temp = X_r_cell[r]
            Lambda_r_temp = Factor_loadings[r]
            Lambda_wan_set.append((1 / (N * T)) * X_r_temp.T @ X_r_temp @ Lambda_r_temp.T)

        m = Factor.shape[0]
        F = Variable((m, T))
        FF = Expression((m * T, T))
        objective = Minimize(V(R, F, Lambda_wan_set, FF))
        problem = Problem(objective)
        problem.solve()
        V_R = (V(R, F.value, Lambda_wan_set, FF.value) ** 2) / (N * T)
        rou = (N + Th) / (N * Th) * np.log((N * Th) / (N + Th))
        IC_R = np.log(V_R) + rou * m
        IC_R_set.append(IC_R)
   
    f_number = np.argmin(IC_R_set) + 1
    return f_number, IC_R_set

# This function executes the local principal component method to simultaneously estimate 
# time-varying factor loading and corresponding factors. 
# R is p X T matrix of excess return, p is the dimension, T is sample size 
# f_number is the number of factors
# Kernel_set is pre-calculating kernel weighting matrix to improve the calculating speed
# h is the bandwidth used for Kernel_set calculating


"""
Description: 
    Computes the time-varying factor loading estimator and corresponding estimated factors 

Input:
    (1) R is p × T excess return matrix, p is the dimension of the portfolio, T is the sample size.
    (2) f_number is an integer, the number of factors.
    (3) Kernel_set is a pre-calculating kernel weighting matrix using bandwidth h
    (4) h is bandwidth used in calculating Kernel_set.
    
Output:
    (1) Factor_loading is T × 1 cell, each element of the cell is f_number × N estimated timevarying factor loadings at each time point.
    (2) Factor_set is a f_number × T matrix, and each row is the estimated factor
"""


def Timevarying_factor_model(R, f_number, Kernel_set, h):
    p, T = R.shape
    Factor_loadings = []
    Fr_cell = []
    X_r_cell = []

    for r in range(T):
        Kernel_r = Kernel_set[:, r]
        X_r = np.zeros((T, p))
        for i in range(p):
            X_i_r = Kernel_r * R[i, :]
            X_r[:, i] = X_i_r
        X_r_cell.append(X_r)
        XX_r = np.dot(X_r.T, X_r)
        XX_evec, XX_evalue = np.linalg.eig(XX_r)
        XX_evalue_dec = np.sort(np.diag(XX_evalue))[::-1]
        dec_index = np.argsort(np.diag(XX_evalue))[::-1]
        F_r = np.dot(XX_evec[:, dec_index[:f_number]], np.sqrt(T))

        # This long 'if' code regularizes the direction of eigenvector
        if r == 0:
            rank1 = abs(F_r[1, :]) > abs(F_r[0, :])
            two_rows = np.array([F_r[0, :], F_r[1, :]])
            direction = np.sign(np.power(two_rows[0, :], 1 - rank1) * np.power(two_rows[1, :], rank1))
        else:
            if r < T - 1:
                two_rows = np.array([F_r[r - 1, :], F_r[r, :]])
                direction_else = np.sign(np.power(two_rows[0, :], 1 - rank1) * np.power(two_rows[1, :], rank1))

                for dir_c in range(len(direction)):
                    if direction_else[dir_c] != direction[dir_c]:
                        F_r[:, dir_c] = -F_r[:, dir_c]

                rank1 = abs(F_r[r + 1, :]) > abs(F_r[r, :])
                two_rows = np.array([F_r[r, :], F_r[r + 1, :]])
                direction = np.sign(np.power(two_rows[0, :], 1 - rank1) * np.power(two_rows[1, :], rank1))
            else:
                two_rows = np.array([F_r[r - 1, :], F_r[r, :]])
                direction_else = np.sign(np.power(two_rows[0, :], 1 - rank1) * np.power(two_rows[1, :], rank1))
                for dir_c in range(len(direction)):
                    if direction_else[dir_c] != direction[dir_c]:
                        F_r[:, dir_c] = -F_r[:, dir_c]

        Fr_cell.append(F_r)
        Lambda_r = 1 / T * np.dot(F_r.T, X_r.T)
        Factor_loadings.append(Lambda_r)

    Factor_set = np.zeros((f_number, T))
    for t in range(T):
        F_t_hat_part1 = np.zeros((f_number, f_number))
        F_t_hat_part2 = np.zeros((f_number, 1))
        factor_loading = Factor_loadings[t]
        for i in range(p):
            F_t_hat_part1 += np.outer(factor_loading[:, i], factor_loading[:, i])
            F_t_hat_part2 += np.outer(factor_loading[:, i], R[i, t])
        F_t_hat = np.dot(np.linalg.inv(F_t_hat_part1), F_t_hat_part2)
        Factor_set[:, t] = F_t_hat.squeeze()

    return Factor_loadings, Factor_set, X_r_cell, Fr_cell, h

This is an example Python code that uses the data_generate function and the Kernel function to generate a kernel weighting matrix for a simulated dataset.

The code first sets the dimension d, the sample size T, and the departure from the null rho. It also calculates a bandwidth h using the rule-of-thumb bandwidth selection method.

The code then generates simulated excess return data Y, population covariance r_cov, and idiosyncratic covariance s_cov using the data_generate function.

Finally, the code creates an empty T by T matrix Kernel_set to store the kernel weighting values. It loops through each pair of time points r and t and calculates the kernel weighting value using the Kernel function. The kernel weighting value is then square-rooted and stored in Kernel_set.

Note that the kernel weighting values are calculated using a normalized bandwidth h (multiplied by the inverse bandwidth in Kernel) to ensure that the kernel values sum to 1 over all time points.

To assess the performance of the proposed estimator, the evaluation statistics for portfolios and covariance matrices are: (1) Risk error: $$ \text { Risk error }=\left|\widehat{W}_t^{\top} \widehat{\Sigma}_{r, t} \widehat{W}_t-W_t^{\top} \Sigma_{r, t} W_t\right|=\left|\frac{1}{1_p^{\top} \widehat{\Sigma}_{r, t}^{-1} 1_p}-\frac{1}{1_p^{\top} \Sigma_{r, t}^{-1} 1_p}\right| $$ where $\hat{W}_t$ and $W_t$ are estimated and true optimal weights at time point t, respectively. $\Sigma_{r, t}$ and $\hat{\Sigma}_{r, t}$ are the true population covariance matrix and its estimate at time point $\mathrm{t}$, respectively. (2) Weight error: the $\ell_2$ norm of the difference between the estimated and true optimal weights. $$ \text { Weight error }=\left\|\widehat{W}_t-W_t\right\|_2=\sqrt{\sum_i\left(\widehat{W}_t-W_t\right)_i^2} $$ (3) Sharpe ratio error: the difference between the estimated and true portfolio Sharpe ratios. $$ \text { SR error }=\left|\frac{\widehat{W}_t^{\top} \widehat{\mu}_t}{\sqrt{\widehat{W}_t^{\top} \widehat{\Sigma}_{r, t} \widehat{W}_t}}-\frac{W_t^{\top} \mu_t}{\sqrt{W_t^{\top} \Sigma_{r, t} W_t}}\right| $$ For the first two DGPs, since the expected asset return is 0, it is not meaningful to compare the Sharpe ratios. And for the last two DGPs, an estimator of the expected return is required to calculate values of the Sharpe ratio. Under our factor structure, we have the estimated expected return $\hat{\mu}_t=\hat{B}_t \frac{1}{T} \sum_{t=1}^T \hat{f}_t$, and for other comparing strategies, we use the sample mean. (4) Covariance error: the Frobenius norm of the difference between estimated and true covariance of assets returns. $$ \text { Covariance error }=\left\|\Sigma_{r, t}-\hat{\Sigma}_{r, t}\right\|_F=\sqrt{\sum_{i j}\left(\Sigma_{r, t}-\hat{\Sigma}_{r, t}\right)_{i j}{ }^2} $$ This metric reflects the goodness of the covariance matrix estimator of assets returns. (5) Residual covariance error: the Frobenius norm of the difference between residual covariance estimator and population error covariance matrix. $$ \text { Residual Covariance error }=\left\|\Sigma_e-\hat{\Sigma}_e\right\|_F=\sqrt{\sum_{i j}\left(\Sigma_e-\hat{\Sigma}_e\right)_{i j}^2} $$

import numpy as np
import cvxpy as cp

def Markowitz_MVP(R_cov):
    """
    Solves the minimum variance portfolio problem

    Arguments:
    R_cov -- numpy array of shape (p, p), the covariance matrix of asset returns

    Returns:
    w -- numpy array of shape (p,), the optimal portfolio weights
    """

    p = R_cov.shape[0]
    N1 = np.ones(p)

    # implementation of minimum variance problem using CVXPY
    w = cp.Variable(p)
    objective = cp.Minimize(cp.quad_form(w, R_cov))
    constraints = [cp.sum(w) == 1]
    problem = cp.Problem(objective, constraints)
    problem.solve()

    # return the optimal portfolio weights
    return np.array(w.value).flatten()
